        <h1>DAN Asia-Pacific News</h1>
        <h2>September Diving Incident Statistics</h2>
        <p align="justify">DAN Asia-Pacific is continuing to share with the recreational   diving community a sample of &ldquo;Calls for Help&rdquo; received at the DAN AP   office. We hope sharing these statistics will further encourage divers   to be aware of potential issues, be prepared and dive carefully.</p>
        <p align="justify"> During the month of September the DAN AP office received calls from a   broad range of countries, including the Philippines, Truk Lagoon, Niue,   the Solomons and Italy.</p>
        <p align="justify"><strong><a href="http://www.danasiapacific.org/main/diving_safety/sept12_incidents.php">CLICK HERE</a> to view a sample of non-fatal calls for help involving DAN AP Members during September 2012.</strong></p>
        <p align="justify">These statistics are based on the calls made directly to DAN   Asia-Pacific. They exclude the calls made directly to the various DAN   Asia-Pacific 24-Hour Emergency Hotlines, or via one of the other DAN   branches: DAN America, DAN Europe, DAN Southern Africa, DAN Japan).   Naturally, the statistics would be far greater if these additional &ldquo;Help   Calls&rdquo; were included.</p>
        <p align="justify">We will continue sharing these statistics with you on a regular basis   in the hope you and your dive buddies are aware that diving incidents   do occur and the importance of being prepared.</p>
        <p align="justify">Being prepared involves becoming a member of an organisation that has   a sole mission of helping divers in need. The Divers Alert Network   (DAN) has 30+ years experience of helping divers in emergency   situations. </p>
        <h2>DAN AP Product Launch: Nautilus Lifeline </h2>
        DAN Asia-Pacific has just added this safety device to its product line. <a href="newsevents/nautilus_lifeline.php">READ MORE<br />
        <br />
        </a>
        <h2>Limited Places Remain for our 'Evening with DAN' Event <br />
        (December 15, HK) </h2>
        <p align="justify">DAN AP Executive Director and renowned speaker, John Lippmann, will  present on two topics that will be of interest and relevance to the Hong Kong  diving community: <em>Hong Kong Diving Fatalities</em> and <em>Emergency  Evacuations</em>.</p>
        <p><strong>EVENT DETAILS<br />
          </strong> <br />
          <strong>When:</strong> Saturday 15th  December&nbsp; <br />
          <strong>Time:</strong> 7.00pm - 10.00pm <br />
          <strong>Where:</strong>&nbsp;Hong Kong Council of Social Service<br />
        Room 201,10/F, Duke of Windsor Social Service Bldg, No.15 Hennessy Rd, Wanchai.<br />
        <strong>Cost:</strong> This is a  free event, sponsored by DAN Asia-Pacific.        <br />
        <strong>Language:</strong> The seminar will be conducted in English. </p>
        <p><strong>HOW TO  BOOK</strong> </p>
        <p>          Send an email to <a href="mailto:communications@danasiapacific.org?subject=An%20Evening%20With%20DAN%20-%20Registration">communications@danasiapacific.org</a> with your:<br />
          <strong>* Name</strong> (Please underline  your&nbsp;family name / last name)<br />
  <strong>* Email</strong><strong><br />
  </strong><strong>* Phone Number</strong><strong><br />
  </strong><strong>*Number of places you wish to reserve.</strong>&nbsp;If  reserving more than one place&nbsp;you <u>must</u> provide the name and email  address of the additional diver/s.<br />
  <strong>* Are You a Current DAN Member? </strong>(Please  indicate Yes or No) </p>
        <p><em>We look  forward to seeing you in December.</em></p>
        <h2>DAN Training in Hong Kong (December) - BOOK NOW </h2>
        <p align="justify">        There are a small number of places remaining in each of the below courses for DAN's upcoming training in Hong Kong this December. It is not often that DAN AP Exeuctive Director, John Lippmann, is in Hong Kong and conducting DAN Training so we encourage you to get involved by registering for one or all of the above courses. </p>
        <p><strong>DAN Oxygen (O2) Provider Course </strong></p>
        <p>Most  injured divers are breathing and require supplemental oxygen.   Oxygen Provision  in Dive Accidents is designed to teach the skills   needed to perform this task  safely and effectively. Topics covered   include diving accident recognition, the  benefits of oxygen provision,   precautions and safety procedures, and oxygen  provision to both   responsive and unresponsive victims. </p>
        <p><em>Who Can Attend?</em> Divers of all levels, from novice to instructor. Minimum age is 14.<br />
        <em>When: </em>Monday 17th December<br />
        <em>Time: </em>5.00pm - 9.00pm<br />
        <em>Cost:</em> AUD$80<br />
        <em>Instructor:</em> McGill  Cheng (Mandarin &amp; English) </p>
        <p><strong>Level 1 Oxygen Instructor Course </strong></p>
        <p align="justify">A person who successfully completes DAN AP&rsquo;s Level 1 O2 Instructor Course becomes a Level 1 DAN Oxygen Instructor permitted to teach the DAN Oxygen Provider course but not the DAN Resuscitation course.</p>
        <p align="justify">Topics covered include recognition of a diving injury; benefits of oxygen provision; handling and storage of oxygen; oxygen delivery systems; teaching the use of the DAN Oxygen Unit; legal issues; and course preparation, standards and procedures.</p>
        <p><em>Who Can Attend?</em> You must have a current DAN O2 Provider certificate, be a current DAN Member, a scuba instructor and over the age of 18.</p>
        <p><em>When: </em>Tuesday 18th December<br />
          <em>Time: </em>10.00am &ndash; 6.00pm<br />
          <em>Cost:</em> AUD$330.00<br />
          <em>Instructor:</em> John Lippmann (English only) </p>
        <p><strong>DAN Diving Medicine for Divers - Part 2</strong></p>
        <p>This courses provides valuable in-depth information to divers on the recognition, management and prevention of specific diving-related injuries. These include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Decompression illness; </li>
          <li>The various types of pulmonary barotrauma: ear, sinus, gastrointestinal, dental and mask barotrauma (among other issues);</li>
          <li>Equipment-related problems; plus</li>
          <li>The recognition and first aid management for anaphylaxis, including the use of an epipen.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><em>Who Can Attend?</em> This course is open to all divers. </p>
        <p><em>When: </em>Wednesday 19th December<br />
          <em>Time: </em>10.00am &ndash; 5.00pm<br />
          <em>Cost:</em> AUD$195 <br />
          <em>Instructor: </em>John Lippmann (English only) </p>
        <h3><a href="_PDF/HKBookingForm2012.pdf">DOWNLOAD THE REGISTRATION FORM HERE</a></h3>
        <p><strong><em>Note:</em> <em>Course numbers are limited so we encourage you to register early. </em></strong></p>
        <h2>DAN Announces the Winner of the July - September Renewing Member Prize </h2>
        <p align="justify">Renewing DAN Asia-Pacific Members in the July - September 2012 quarter had the opportunity to win a fantastic 7 Night Liveaboard Diving Safari with Worldwide Dive and Sail and the Siren Fleet. Valued at AUD$2,875. </p>
        <p align="justify">All Members had to do was renew their coverage BEFORE it expired in order to be entered into the draw. </p>
        <p align="justify">The ecstatic winners are Kaz and Chris from South Australia, who had to say:</p>
        <p align="justify"><em>For a very very long time we have&nbsp;wanted to visit Palau and the Jellyfish Lake,   so we are super excited to have won such a fantastic prize! Thank you DAN and   Worldwide Dive &amp;&nbsp;Sail. </em></p>
        <p align="justify"><em>Keep up the good work guys, it's a great comfort&nbsp;to   know&nbsp;DAN are behind the diving community worldwide.</em></p>
        <p align="justify"><strong>The prize on offer for renewing Members in the October - December 2012 quarter is a 7 Night Dive Holiday at the Renowned Walindi Plantation Resort in PNG (Valued at AUD$2,600). <a href="http://www.danasiapacific.org/main/sponsors/walindi_prize.php">CLICK HERE</a> for more prize information</strong>.</p>
        <p align="justify">If your DAN AP renewal falls within this quarter make sure you renew your coverage BEFORE it expires so you have a chance at winning this great prize. </p>
        <h2>Alert Diver May - August 2012 Issue</h2>
        <p>The May - August 2012 issue of <em>Alert Diver </em>magazine is an electronic issue and was sent to Members on the 13th September. </p>
        <p>As always, you will  find a great selection of&nbsp;interesting and valuable&nbsp;dive health and  safety articles, including:</p>
        <p>          - Could breath-hold diving after  scuba cause decompression illness?<br />
          -&nbsp;2007 Diving-related fatalities<br />
          - A case of equipment failure: A personal incident report by Dr Peter Buzzacott<br />
          - When you least expect it. Bob  Halstead's personal experience with salt-water aspiration.</p>
        <p>If you have not received the latest issue in your inbox, send us an <a href="mailto:marketing@danasiapacific.org">email</a> with your current Member Number and the link to the e-issue will be sent to you.  </p>
        <h2>DAN AP Sponsors the QLD Dive Industry Safety Awards <br />
  (Run by Workplace Health &amp; Safety QLD) </h2>
        <p>DAN Asia-Pacific is sponsoring the upcoming  QLD Government's Dive Safety Awards. These awards recognise safety champions in Queensland's dive   and snorkelling industry and are an opportunity for tour operators to   showcase their world class safety procedures.</p>
        <p>If you, or  someone you know, work in the QLD diving or recreational snorkelling industry why  not recommend they enter the Dive Safety Awards 2012? </p>
        <p><a href="http://www.deir.qld.gov.au/workplace/events/dive-safety-awards/2012/how-to-enter/index.htm">CLICK HERE</a> for details on how to enter. Applicants need to submit a film of their emergency response drill for a missing diver or snorkeller. </p>
        <p>Entries  close <strong>12 September 2012</strong> so start  planning your entry and for inspiration check out last  year&rsquo;s <a href="http://www.deir.qld.gov.au/workplace/events/dive-safety-awards/2012/resources/index.htm#winners">winners</a>.  <br />
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />
        For more information about the QLD Government's Dive Safety Awards email <a href="mailto:safe@justice.qld.gov.au">safe@justice.qld.gov.au</a> or call  Workplace Health and Safety Queensland on 1300 369 915. </p>
        <h2>DAN Asia-Pacific Monthly Diving Incident Statistics - July 2012 </h2>
        <p align="justify"> DAN Asia-Pacific is continuing to share with the recreational diving community a sample of &ldquo;Calls for Help&rdquo;   received at the DAN AP office. We hope  sharing these statistics will   further encourage divers to be aware of potential  issues, be prepared   and dive carefully.</p>
        <p align="justify">During the month of July the DAN AP office received calls from a broad range of countries, including Indonesia, Fiji, Thailand, and Australia. The need for help  ranged from stroke, a motorbike accident, DCI and Ear Barotrauma. Two serious cases required an Emergency Medical Evacuation by air to another country for Treatment. One of these evacuations was at the cost of $70,000.</p>
        <p align="justify"><a href="http://www.danasiapacific.org/main/diving_safety/july12_incidents.php">CLICK HERE</a><strong> to view a sample of non-fatal calls for help involving DAN AP Members during July 2012. </strong></p>
        <p align="justify">These statistics are based on the calls   made directly to DAN  Asia-Pacific. They exclude the calls made directly   to the various DAN  Asia-Pacific 24-Hour Emergency Hotlines, or via one   of the other DAN branches:  DAN America, DAN Europe, DAN Southern   Africa, DAN Japan). Naturally, the  statistics would be far greater if   these additional &ldquo;Help Calls&rdquo; were included.</p>
        <p align="justify">We will continue sharing these statistics   with you on a  regular basis in the hope you and your dive buddies are   aware that diving  incidents do occur and the importance of being   prepared.&nbsp;</p>
        <p align="justify">Being prepared involves becoming a member   of an organisation  that has a sole mission of helping divers in need.   The Divers Alert Network  (DAN) has 30+ years experience of helping   divers in emergency situations.</p>
        <h2>DAN AP Launches Member-Only Portal on Website </h2>
        <p>We are delighted to annouce the launch of a Member-Only Portal on the DAN AP website. Our objective is to share with Members, a range of materials that will further develop their diving health and safety knowledge and skills. The Member-Only section will contain:</p>
        <ul>
          <li> <strong>Online Seminars</strong>: In a first for DAN AP, you will be able to access Online Seminars on a range of topics, such as <em>Diver Fatalities</em> and <em>Medications and Diving</em>. The first seminar ready to be viewed via the Portal is &quot;<em>Diver Accident Management</em>&quot;.</li>
          <li> <strong>Reports on DCI and Diving Fatalities</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong> Findings from recent Research Initiatives</strong>. </li>
          <li> <strong>Articles from past issues of <em>Alert Diver</em> magazine</strong>. </li>
          <li> <strong>Dowloads of Books</strong>, commencing with<em> Diving Medicine for Scuba Divers</em> and the <em>Sports Diving Medical</em>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>          We will continue adding to the website. New Online Seminars will be announced in <em>Alert Diver </em>magazine and <em>Deeper with DAN</em>.</p>
        <p>          As a Member-Only benefit the site can only be accessed with a current DAN Asia-Pacific Member Number.</p>
        <p><strong>Current Members can log into the website by</strong> <a href="http://www.danasiapacific.org/main/member_only/index.php">CLICKING HERE</a>. </p>
        <h2>Updated DAN Doc Website</h2>
        <p align="justify">DAN AP&rsquo;s dedicated diving medical issues website has been  given a facelift. If you have a medical condition, concern or question relating  to dive health and safety then the DAN Doc website is for you. </p>
        <p align="justify">The dedicated website addresses a broad range of medical  issues from decompression illness, the nervous system, medications to  cardiovascular fitness and much more.</p>
        <p align="justify"><a href="http://www.danasiapacific.org/main/diving_safety/DAN_Doc/main.html">CLICK HERE</a> to visit the DAN Doc website.</p>
        <h2>Have You Ever Wondered How DAN Helps Divers? </h2>
        <p>Speaking  to divers throughout the Asia-Pacific region a recurring question concerns &ldquo;<em>How  Can DAN Help Me?&rdquo; </em></p>
        <p>Divers are often concerned that a DAN office does not  exist in each country of the Asia-Pacific. However, the reality is that a  physical office in each country does not affect the level of assistance and  care provided to the diver. Systems created to best assist a member are  activated as soon as a call for help is received via a DAN 24-hour emergency  hotline. </p>
        <p>To  assist divers, DAN AP has created a flow chart that highlights, step-by-step,  what happens from the moment a call for help is received from a Member. </p>
        <p>The  Flow Chart can be downloaded from the Dive Safety section on the DAN AP  website. We hope this will provide divers with a simple overview of DAN&rsquo;s  assistance process.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
        <p>With  30+ years experience helping divers in trouble, the Divers Alert Network is the  expert in diver accident management.</p>
        <p><a href="_pdf/How_DAN_Helps.pdf">CLICK HERE</a><strong> to Download the Step-by-Step Flowchart.</strong>  </p>
